Hi Stefan,

As a general policy we flag patches applied in the build process as we should really be working with upstream directly. In this case I understand you're backporting a capability that's already upstream. That's fine. In the case of projects such as Linux and u-boot we maintain our own forks but follow upstream's development methodology. As such, please send this as patch against openbmc/linux dev-6.1 to openbmc@lists.ozlabs.org:

https://github.com/openbmc/docs/blob/master/kernel-development.md

Hello Andrew,

the patch I am applying to OpenBMC's Linux kernel is only temporary. The patch that will be going into upstream (6.4 I was hoping, but more likely 6.5) is here: https://lore.kernel.org/linux-integrity/20230418-engste-gastwirtschaft-601fb389bba5@brauner/T/#sec-pillar-team

However, for this 6.5 patch some infrastructure is required that was added in 6.3 (support for STATX_CHANGE_COOKIE): https://lore.kernel.org/lkml/20230124193025.185781-1-jlayton@kernel.org/

So I am not sure what to do at the moment. Once OpenBMC moves to 6.3 kernel we only need to apply that single patch, but for anything before 6.3 we would need to apply Jeff Layton's whole series of 8 patches (at least). So I currently prefer to only apply this single 2-line patch that solves the issue I had encountered.

    Stefan

Yes, I understand. Please just send the kernel patch that you've integrated here to openbmc@lists.ozlabs.org. We will apply that to openbmc/linux dev-6.1 and that will eliminate this CI failure (as this specific metadata patch goes away once the kernel is bumped).

The changes are okay, but they need to go into the openbmc kernel tree.

We don't allow patching in the meta layers as per https://github.com/openbmc/docs/blob/master/meta-layer-guidelines.md#meta-layers-should-not-patch-projects-that-exist-within-the-openbmc-tree
